\topic{Semi-Empirical Mass Formula (SEMF): Mass Parabolas, Stability}
Now that we have found the binding energy, we can write an expression for the mass. The mass formula comes out to be \textbf{parabolas}, and the minimum mass corresponds to stability\footnote{This is an important point: notice in Eq.~\ref{BAZ}, the smaller the mass, the larger the binding energy, and binding energy is a negative term, so the smaller the total energy, the more stable. }.
\begin{align}
B(A,Z) &= \left[ Z m_H + N m_n - m(A,Z) \right] c^2  \label{BAZ}\\
m(A,Z) c^2 &= \left[ Z m_H + N m_n \right] c^2 - B(A,Z) \\
&= Z^2 (\cdots) + Z(\cdots) + C 
\end{align}
Since the $m(A,Z)$ comes out to be a parabola for constant A $m(Z)$(notice, we are fixing A!!!), then there exists a $Z$ such that $m(Z)$ is minimum, and this is the most stable one. Of course this is a simple approximation that does not take into account stuffs like paring effect yet. 

If we take the derivative of the $m(A,Z)$ equation and set it to zero, we find $Z_{min}$ to be: 
\eqn{ Z_{min} \approx \frac{A/2}{2 + \frac{1}{4} \frac{a_c}{a_{sym}} A^{3/4}} }
At small A, $Z_{min} \sim \frac{A}{2}$. At large A, $Z_{min} < \frac{A}{2} \sim 0.41 A$. 

If we go back to our parabola graph of M vs Z fixing A, at $Z > Z_{min}$, there are too many protons; $Z < Z_{min}$, there are too many neutrons. By nature these nuclei want to undergo decay to reach stability. 

Proton-rich nuclei go through $\beta^+$ decays: \ce{p^+ \to n + \beta^+ + \gamma}, or Electron Capture (E.C.): \ce{p + e^- \to n + \gamma}. Example: \ce{^{16}_9 F_7 \to ^{16}_8 O_8 + \beta^+ + \gamma}. 

Neutron-rich nuclei go through $\beta^-$ decays: \ce{n \to p + \beta^- + \gamma}. Example: \ce{^{16}_7 N_9 \to ^{16}_8 O_8 + \beta^- + \gamma}.

The important thing to keep in mind for beta decay is that $M_{final} < M_{initial}$, that is, goes down on the M vs. Z curve.

